Part I¶

General impact of macro-nutrients in the calories content of food¶

by (FUMBAH ELVIS NJI)¶

DATASET OVERVIEW¶

Introduce the dataset : Food Composition Database.¶

It contains data for various types of food including the amounts of different nutrients found in the foods:

Explanations of the columns¶

  • Vitamin A: 1 IU is the biological equivalent of 0.3 mcg retinol,
  • Vitamin A measured in RAE, means the amount of vitamin A that we can obtain from a certain amount of calories.
  • Retinol (vitamin A)
  • riboflavin (vitamin B2)
  • Niacin (b coplext E),
  • Pantothenic Acid(b5 E)
  • Thiamin(B1 E)
  • lipids any of a class of organic compounds that are fatty acids or their derivatives and are insoluble in water but soluble * in organic solvents.
  • Monounsaturated fats are healthy fats;
  • Ash refers to any inorganic material, such as minerals, present in food. It's called ash because it's residue that remains after heating removes water and organic material such as fat and protein.
  • Fiber is a type of carbohydrate that the body can’t digest
  • The phytochemicals include: Carotene,Cryptoxanthin, Lutein and Zeaxanthin, Lycopene,
  • lipids Cholesterol
  • Total Lipid = Cholesterol + fats
  • Kilocalories = energy foods
  • Choline :A water-soluble vitamin. Measured in milligrams (mg).
  • Category : general category of food that this item belongs to.
  • Description : A full description of this food item, including its category and some sub categories.
  • Nutrient Data Bank Number : A unique ID for this food item.
  • The Data set also contains mirco-nutrients like MINERALS AND VITAMINS, etc

Source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/trolukovich/nutritional-values-for-common-foods-and-products/download?datasetVersionNumber=1

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

we also have data on the composition of these main nutrients that might help in our analyis: ie

issue: inconsistent units in the whole dataset¶

Transform all the numerical data except calories to have the same measurement (gram)

In [13]:
#we will use Regular Expression Module to help me clean the data
import re
#Loop in each non-numerical features except the name and food_categories feature 
for col in nutrients_df.drop(['name','food_categories'],axis = 1).select_dtypes(exclude = ['number']).columns:
    for i in nutrients_df[col]:
        if i == '0' or i == 0:
            pass
        else:
            point = re.findall('[a-zA-Z]+',i)[0]
            replace = []
            if point == 'mg':
                for j in nutrients_df[col]:
                    if j == '0' or j == 0:
                        replace.append(float(j))
                    else:
                        replace.append(float(re.sub('[a-zA-Z]','',j))/1000)
            elif point == 'mcg':
                for j in nutrients_df[col]:
                    if j == '0' or j == 0:
                        replace.append(float(j))
                    else:
                        replace.append(float(re.sub('[a-zA-Z]','',j))/1000000)  
            else:
                 for j in nutrients_df[col]:
                    if j == '0' or j == 0:
                        replace.append(float(j))
                    else:       
                        replace.append(float(re.sub('[a-zA-Z]','',j)))
                        
            nutrients_df[col] = replace    
            nutrients_df.rename({col:col+'(g)'}, axis =1, inplace = True)
            break

The plots shows 03 distinct region samples with calories lower than 400, samples with calories between 400 andd 700 and samples around 900. however, the samples around 900 need more investigations as they seem aberantes.

we will use the .agg method of the DataFrame to gain information about the mean, median, std, skewness to confirm that the data is really skweed before we can consider calories greater than 800 to be aberante statistical rule of thumbs is:

  • If the skewness is between -0.5 and 0.5, the data are fairly symmetrical
  • If the skewness is between -1 and — 0.5 or between 0.5 and 1, the data are moderately skewed
  • If the skewness is less than -1 or greater than 1, the data are highly skewed

Turn out that our data is skewed, let explore what food is considered to be an outlier based on the Calories.

  • As our data is skewed enough, we would not rely on the mean to find the outlier; instead, we would apply the IQR method which is based on the median.
  • Interquartile Range is based on the data position.

IQR would be based on the 25% position or Q1 and 75% position or Q3. With the IQR method, we could decide which data are considered an outlier based on the upper or lower limit which is:

  • Lower Limit= Q1–1.5 * IQR
  • Upper Limit= Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
In [21]:
#Specifying the limit
def get_outliers(feature):
    cal_Q1 = nutrients_df.describe()[feature]['25%']
    cal_Q3 = nutrients_df.describe()[feature]['75%']
    cal_IQR = cal_Q3 - cal_Q1
    return  nutrients_df[(nutrients_df[feature] < 1.5 * (cal_Q1 - cal_IQR)) | (nutrients_df[feature] > 1.5 * (cal_Q3 + cal_IQR)) ]['food_categories'].value_counts(ascending=True)
